<span class="model_question">
[Type: Diagram showing an isosceles triangle ABD and a straight line ABC. Angles are marked with $x^{\circ}$, $y^{\circ}$, and $w^{\circ}$] The diagram shows an isosceles triangle ABD and the straight line ABC. BA=BD. $x:y=2:1$. Work out the value of $w$.
</span>
<script type="application/json" class="ai-diagram-data">
{"type": "triangle", "description": "isosceles triangle"}
</script>
<div class="model_answer">
Let $x = 2y$. Since triangle $ABD$ is isosceles, $\angle BAD = \angle BDA = x$. <span class="marking-code">[P1]</span><br>
The sum of angles in a triangle is $180^\circ$, so $x + x + y = 180^\circ$. <span class="marking-code">[P1]</span><br>
Substituting $x = 2y$, we get $2y + 2y + y = 180^\circ$, which simplifies to $5y = 180^\circ$.<br>
Therefore, $y = \frac{180}{5} = 36^\circ$.<br>
Then $x = 2y = 2 \times 36 = 72^\circ$.<br>
Since $w$ and $x$ are supplementary angles, $w = 180 - y = 180 - 36 = 144^\circ$.<br>
Alternatively, $w = x + x = 2x = 2 \times 72 = 144^\circ$. <span class="marking-code">[P1]</span><br>
$w = 144^\circ$ <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span>
</div>

